[normal](i)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The report has chosen not to evaluate the contribution of clouds in the summary figure TS.7 attached below.  There is 
[normal]an “aerosol-cloud” factor of 
[normal]~
[normal]0.5
[normal]5 W/m
[normal]2
[normal] with 
[normal]a 
[normal]relative
[normal] error bar up to 
[normal]~
[normal]1.3
[normal] W/m
[normal]2
[normal]. This is inadequate and underestimates the contribution 
[normal]of clouds to the radi
[normal]ation balance of the planet.  (
[normal]Double CO
[normal]2
[normal] forcing is 
[normal]~ 3.7 W/m
[normal]2 
[normal])
[normal]Marine stratocumulus 
[normal](layer) 
[normal]clouds 
[normal]cover 30% of the ocean surface, ~ 20% of the global planetary surface.  Numerical Weather Prediction (NWP) models (i.e. weather fore
[normal]casting models) have difficulty in getting sufficient and correct cloud fr
[normal]action / cover.  In 2008 there 
[normal]was a large VOCALS project which aimed at understanding the processes, which generate and dissipate these clouds.
[normal]  NWP models improved, but these solve
[normal] the equations on grids on 1 to 10km.  Climate models have gridpoints ev
[normal]ery hundreds of kilometres,  underestimate stratocumulus cloud cover.  With incoming solar radiation of 1350 W/m
[normal]2 
[normal], and a change of reflection /albedo in the equator regions from 
[normal]20% t
[normal]o 80% depending on non-cloud or cloud cover, combined with the under
[normal]-
[normal]representation of Marine Stratocumulus clouds
[normal] in the climate models
[normal], then 3.7W/m
[normal]2 
[normal] is far smaller than the potential errors in the reflected solar radiation.  Even a modest error in the cloud cover would le
[normal]a
[normal]d to feedback uncertainties of 10’s W/m
[normal]2
[normal]. The IPCC report g
[normal]ives a negative feedback of ~ 0.5
[normal]5 W/m
[normal]2
[normal] up to 
[normal]~1.3
[normal] W/m
[normal]2 
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]for the cloud 
[normal]contribution. Th
[normal]is an 
[normal]unde
[normal]restim
[normal]ate of the cloud component forcing, which by
[normal] 
[normal]far dominates the uncertainties provided by aerosols etc.
[normal] 
[normal](see Figure TS.7 below taken fro
[normal]m a preparatory copy of the IPCC report)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The small error bars and the lac
[normal]k of discussion
[normal] / application is a hugely significant oversight.
