[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](v)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]    
[normal]Climate models are unable to describe (resolve) 
[normal]some of 
[normal]the important processes
[normal] which control the climate.   
[normal]The location
[normal] of “blocking anticy
[normal]clones”, high pressures in the Atlantic
[normal],
[normal] largely determine the flux of warm moist air to the North Pole.  Climate models cannot resolve these large scale meteorological features, basically because the smaller scale eddies in the atmosphere, which drive and maintain these large structures, are to
[normal]o small and cannot be seen or resolved by climate models.  Thus the transport of heat to the poles (the main kinematic function of the atmosphere on the global scale) is misrepresented.  The critical differences between the Northern Hemisphere circulation,
[normal] where the frequency of
[normal] “blocks” are under-represented 
[normal]and the Southern Hemisphere circulation, where blocks are far to
[normal]o frequent
[normal],
[normal] is important.  This inadequacy 
[normal]is of significant concern
[normal] in the prediction of future climates
[normal].  The increase in intensity of 
[normal]Southern North Atlantic hurricanes
[normal], observed, understood and predicted by meteor
[normal]o
[normal]logists, and which have significant impact o
[normal]n the North American climate is
[normal] not seen in climate models. The resolution in climate models is just not good enough to produce the
[normal]m as they are driven from smaller scale convective systems and easterly waves, too small for these models.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](vi)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]      The overall Meridional Heat f
[normal]lux 
[normal](MHF) 
[normal]in the climate models is, for the above reasons 
[normal]given in section (iv)
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]not adequate to simulate the 
[normal]flux of warm moist air to Artic regions
[normal].  
[normal]This 
[normal]issue 
[normal]is controversial
[normal] and topical but
[normal] 
[normal]getting these ideas into the mainstream 
[normal]scientific discussion 
[normal]is difficult 
[normal]partly 
[normal]due to the 
[normal]consequence 
[normal](
[normal]and a negative aspect
[normal])
[normal] of the peer review process
[normal], 
[normal]whi
[normal]ch is by n
[normal]ature reticent to
[normal]wards
[normal] new ideas.  
[normal]I would argue 
[normal]MHF 
[normal]is critically 
[normal]important to explain why
[normal] the Arctic Ice melt is very much more rapid than the models 
[normal]have 
[normal]predict
[normal]ed
[normal].  
[normal]Tentatively I would
[normal] suggest, that in just a few years time, the Arctic will be ice free
[normal] in September. (Ice-free I define as &lt; 15% broken ice).  Artic Polar ice retreats 
[normal]and advances each year, but 
[normal]Figure 1 below, shows that over the past 30 years the Arctic Ice volume has been very 
[normal]much 
[normal]significantly reduced.  This process can be reversed (a
[normal]nd hence why the climate sceptics and the climate green lobby 
[normal]both object to this hypothesis)  Yet
[normal] the overall assertion is that the sophisticated climate models do NOT
[normal] replicate this rapid decline (e
[normal]lephant in the room) and the “climate modelling industry
[normal]” largely ignore this.   
